    "k̸ =j̸ =yd k = D.(28)We can define the Lagrange function L as follows:L(d 1, • • •, d K, λ) = -log(p y + D) + k̸ =j̸ =y log(p y + d k) + λ • k̸ =j̸ =y d k -D.(29)Now we can calculate the gradients:∂L ∂d k = -1 py+d k + λ, k ̸ = j ̸ = y, ∂L ∂λ = k̸ =j̸ =y d k -D.(30)Let ∂L ∂d k = 0 and ∂L ∂λ = 0, we have:-1 py+d k + λ = 0, k ̸ = j ̸ = y, k̸ =j̸ =y d k -D = 0,(31)and thus, we have:d k = D K -2, k ̸ = j ̸ = y.",
    "(32)So, the minimization value is:-log(p y + D) + k̸ =j̸ =y log(p y - D K -2).Now, combining with Eq.",
    "( 27), we have: f 1 (p) -f 2 (p,K -2) = (K -2) log p y -log(p y - D K -2) -log(p y + D) -log p y = D • log p y -log(p y -D K-2) D K-2 - log(p y + D) -log p y D.(33)Recall the nature of the difference, we have log p y -log(p y -D K-2) D K-2 = 1 p y -α > 1 p y > 1 p y + β = log(p y + D) -log p y D,(34)which leads to the inequality:log p y -log(p y -D K-2) D K-2 > log(p y + D) -log p y D.(35)Thus, we have:f 1 (p) > f 2 (p, D).",
    "(36)Now, considering p k = p(k|x 2), ∀k ∈ {1, • • •, K}, D = p(y|x 1) -p(y|x 2), and d k = p(k|x 2) -p(k|x 1), k ̸ = j ̸ = y, for the derivatives of f 1 (p) and f 2 (p, D), we have: f 1 (p) = K k=1 log p k = K k=1 log p(k|x 2),(37) and:Therefore, combining with Eq.",
    "( 36), we obtain:1 K k=1 A + log p(k|x 1) 2 > 1 K k=1 A + log p(k|x 2) 2(39)Under the assumption that p(j|x 1) = p(j|x 2), and log p(y|x 1) > log p(y|x 2), i.e., p(y|x 1) > p(y|x 2), we have:1 p(j|x 1) • A + log p(y|x 1) K k=1 A + log p(k|x 1) 2 > 1 p(j|x 2) • A + log p(y|x 2) K k=1 A + log p(k|x 2) 2 (40) Thus, we conclude: ∂L NNCE ∂p(j|x 1) > ∂L NNCE ∂p(j|x 2).This completes the proof."
